    <h3>Project Work</h3>
    <br>
    <span>Draft a set of questions that you want to ask to a famous player (international, national, regional). Visit
        him/her and take an interview with the help of the questions. Prepare a news article including his/her struggle
        and achievement.</span>
    <br>
    <br>
    This project is based on the interview taken with <b>Sita Rana Magar</b>, the batting all-rounder of Nepal
    women&rsquo;s cricket team who started off her cricket in her school to getting into the national team of Nepal.
    <br>
    <br>
    <b>Questions</b>
    <br>
    <br>
    1. Take us through you childhood and initial cricketing days? What age did you start playing cricket?
    <br>
    <br>
    2. Have you always been a sports fanatic and how did cricket happen? Did you play any other sport growing up?
    <br>
    <br>
    3. When and how did you get into the national cricket team? Which year did you make your debut?
    <br>
    <br>
    4. How was cricket back then in Nepal when you started playing it? Has it evolved over the years?
    <br>
    <br>
    5. What is the structure or pathway for any aspiring cricketer to play for the national team in Nepal?
    <br>
    <br>
    6. Do we have sufficient cricket academies in Nepal? Where do most of the girls train in Nepal?
    <br>
    <br>
    7. What do you enjoy more, batting or bowling and why?
    <br>
    <br>
    8. There have been some serious issues regarding contracts and pay scales for players, what do you think is the main
    reason behind that?
    <br>
    <br>
    9. Tell us about your role at APF? How do you manage these roles?
    <br>
    <br>
    10. What is that one thing needed to improve the state of women&rsquo;s cricket in Nepal?
    <br>
    <br>
    <br>
    <b>Excerpts from the Interview are as follows:</b>
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>1. Take us through you childhood and initial cricketing days? What age did you start playing cricket?</span>
    <br>
    I used to play all the sports in my school, when women&rsquo;s cricket was first introduced in Nepal; I was just 13
    years old. My teacher encouraged me to take up cricket and train for the same at the time I was a 7th grader.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>2. Have you always been a sports fanatic and how did cricket happen? Did you play any other sport growing
        up?</span>
    <br>
    Yes, I am a complete sports fanatic. I was always involved in some or the other sport in my school days and so my
    teachers asked me to take up cricket as well and have a hand on it. Football has always been my game I believe and
    so I always dreamt of becoming a footballer.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>3. When and how did you get into the national cricket team? Which year did you make your debut?</span>
    <br>
    My debut in the national team came in the year 2007. I started off playing cricket in my school days for the school
    team when I got selected for the regional team- Nepal Jung and then I also participated in Nepal&rsquo;s first ever
    women&rsquo;s cricket tournament where I emerged as the best bowler and eventually got selected for the national
    team.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>4. How was cricket back then in Nepal when you started playing it? Has it evolved over the years?</span>
    <br>
    When I started playing, it was a huge challenge. There were not any training centres, there was a lot of social
    pressure and there were rarely any girls who wished to take up cricket. But today, I can say that it is slowly
    evolving.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>5. What is the structure or pathway for any aspiring cricketer to play for the national team in Nepal?</span>
    <br>
    The structure goes like getting into the district team first and then the regional. Once they have played enough
    games and emerge as deserving players, they go on to get selected in the national team.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>6. Do we have sufficient cricket academies in Nepal? Where do most of the girls train in Nepal?</span>
    <br>
    I am residing in Kathmandu since the year 2008 so I know only about the academies that are here in Kathmandu. Here,
    girls enrol with the Kathmandu Cricket Training Center (KCTC) and Baluwatar Cricket Academy (BCA).
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>7. What do you enjoy more, batting or bowling and why?</span>
    <br>
    Being a batting all-rounder, I have always enjoyed batting more.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>8. There have been some serious issues regarding contracts and pay scales for players, what do you think is
        the main reason behind that?</span>
    <br>
    The suspension of CAN is the main problem. When the CAN was working, all the regions were informed about tournaments
    so that players can be ready in time.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>9. Tell us about your role at APF? How do you manage these roles?</span>
    <br>
    Armed Police Force (APF) is a government organisation which gives priority to all sports where more than five
    hundred players play various sports. It is our duty to play but at times we are even asked to work for the security
    of the nation as well.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>10. What is that one thing needed to improve the state of women&rsquo;s cricket in Nepal?</span>
    <br>
    Proper management is required highly. Only this can improve the state of women&rsquo;s cricket in Nepal right now.
    <br>
    <br>
    <br>
    <p style="text-align: center; font-weight: bold;">Sita Rana Magar: Faith and Inspiration</p>
    <br>
    Sita Rana Magar is a Nepali cricketer and an All Rounder of Nepali National Cricket team. She is considered one of
    the greatest batsmen in the history of Nepali cricket. She was born on 5 March, 1992.
    <br>
    <br>
    Sita Rana Magar, the batting all-rounder, is the name that continues to inspire many womens in Nepal. She was a
    complete sports fanatic since her childhood. She was always involved in some or the other sport in her school days.
    On the beginning of her sports journey, she dreamt of becoming a footballer. She believed that Football has always
    been her game. But later her sports teacher encouraged her to take up cricket and trained her for the same when she
    was studying at 7th grade.
    <br>
    <br>
    Her debut in the national team came in the year 2007. She started off playing cricket in her school days for the
    school team when she got selected for the regional team- Nepal Jung and then she also participated in Nepal&rsquo;s
    first ever women&rsquo;s cricket tournament where she emerged as the best bowler and eventually got selected for the
    national team.
    <br>
    <br>
    She have really struggled in her journey of becoming a national player. It was a huge challenge for her. There were
    not any training centers, there was a lot of social pressure and there were rarely any girls who wished to take up
    cricket. Despite of this, she ended up becoming a successful player.
    <br>
    <br>
    She bats Left Handed and bowls Left-art medium-fast. She played in the Women's Asia Cup T20, 2016. She has also
    played in the 2014 Asian Games as a part of the Nepal women's national cricket team.
    <br>
    <br>
    Magar made her international debut in January 2019 against China in Thailand women's T20 smash tournament. She also
    represented Nepal in the 2019 ICC Women's Qualifier Asia in Bangkok, Thailand. This is a tournament which is an Asia
    region qualifier for the 2019 ICC Women's World Twenty20 Qualifier as well as the 2020 Women's Cricket World Cup
    Qualifier tournaments, with the top team progressing to both of them. In October 2021, she was named in Nepal's side
    for the 2021 ICC Women's T20 World Cup Asia Qualifier tournament in the United Arab Emirates.
    <br>
